(1, 2, 'Unix Basics', 'Introduction to major Unix commands', '<h4><em><strong>Lab 1: Unix Basics</strong></em></h4>\n<p>The following files must be submitted in Unix</p>\n<ul>\n<li>allfiles</li>\n<li>sessions_log</li>\n</ul>\n<h4><em><strong>Objectives</strong></em></h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Be able to perform basic Unix operations for establishing directories and manipulating files within user directories.</li>\n<li>Get a feel of how to use the editor Pico.</li>\n<li>Be able to edit, compile and run C++ programs in Unix.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Unix Commands/Concepts Covered ...</p>\n<ul>\n<li>pwd , cd , ls , mkdir , rmdir , cp (-r) , mv , rm , cat , more</li>\n<li>I/O redirection: &lt; &gt;</li>\n<li>Unix editors: pico</li>\n<li>Special directories: bin, home(~), current (.), and parent (..)</li>\n<li>Command line syntax: command [-options] argument list</li>\n</ul>\n<h4><em><strong>Instructions</strong></em></h4>\n<p>FIRST read the entire assignment (If you have a small screen monitor you could print out the assignment to simplify things). You should do a dry run of the steps, then repeat the steps with the session logging turned on for keeps!</p>\n<p>Many of these operations will be used throughout the class and in future classes (for CIS students at least) so paying attention won''t hurt.</p>\n<hr /><ol>\n<li>Before you get started you will be recording all your work so you and your instructor can review it. In order to do this turn on session logging (journaling) so that all interactions between you and the system are written to a file &#40;default name is "typescript"&#41;. The Unix command: <code>script session_log</code></li>\n<li>\n<p>Let''s take a closer look at dealing with directories. Follow the instructions below:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Get the full path name of the directory you are in ( <code>pwd</code> ).</li>\n<li>list the contents in compressed form ( <code>ls</code> )</li>\n<li>with all attributes listed ( <code>ls -l</code> ),</li>\n<li>with all files, including hidden files, listed ( <code>ls -a</code> OR <code>ls -al</code> ).</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Go back to your home directory ( <code>cd ~</code> ) and list all the hidden files there.</p>\n</li>\n<li>Go to your home LAB directory ( <code>cd ~/COP3014L</code> ). Create a subdirectory named "playarea", to be used throughout this lab. The command is mkdir. <em>NOTE: If you need to START OVER, you can erase this directory and all its sub-directories using this command <code>rm -r ~/COP3014L/playarea</code> </em></li>\n<li>\n<p>Go to directory playarea. Use an editor of your choice (for example, pico)to create a file named ''first'' that contains the eight lines:</p>\n<pre>This is only a test file</pre>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Make two copies of ''first'', calling them ''second'' and ''third''. The copy command is <code>cp</code>.</p>\n<p><code>cp original_file copied_file</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Make subdirectories of playarea named ''chicken'' and ''egg''. Copy file ''second'' to directory ''chicken'' and file ''first'' to directory ''egg''. An example of copying a file into another directory is shown below:</p>\n<p><code>cp filename.txt DIRECTORY/</code></p>\n<p><strong><em>NOTE: This copies "filename.txt" into DIRECTORY.</em></strong></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>At times it be useful to view a file without having to be in "edit" mode. Here are a few ways of doing that using <code>cat</code> and <code>more</code>.</p>\n<p>Try this way to view the contents of file ''first'':</p>\n<code>cat first</code>\n<p>Try this way also:</p>\n<p><code>more first</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>In Unix, you can redirect standard output to go to a file. This output redirection is very useful if you want to save the output of a command to a file rather than just letting it flash across the screen and eventually scroll away from view. Let''s redirect the output from the command pwd so that the output is written to file ''pwd.output''.</p>\n<p>Type in the following command and be able to explain how output redirection ("&gt;") works.</p>\n<p><code>pwd &gt; pwd.output</code></p>\n<p><code>ls</code></p>\n<p><code>cat pwd.output</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>In this step we will add an extension to "first" by add the ".txt" ending to it. We can append the extension using the following step</p>\n<p><code>mv filename filename.txt</code></p>\n<p>Next, let''s place the file in your ~/public directory. (If public does dont exist create it in your home holder using e.g. <code>mkdir ~/public</code> )</p>\n<p><code>mv first.txt ~/public</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Now lets try delete a directory. First try deleteing ''egg'' using the following command and try see if it works.</p>\n<p><code>rmdir egg</code></p>\n<p>If anything was in egg it should have shown you an erro telling you that it can''t do that. Let''s try delete all the files with egg first and see what happens.</p>\n<p><strong><em>HINT: In unix star ( * ) is used as a wild card and selects all items -&gt; Go step by step and pay attention!</em></strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li><code>cd egg</code> -&gt; Open up the directory...</li>\n<li><code>ls </code> -&gt; take a peek inside...</li>\n<li><code>rm *</code> -&gt; removes everything inside the directory...</li>\n<li><code>ls</code> -&gt; See if anything is left...</li>\n<li><code>cd ..</code> -&gt; go back to try again...</li>\n<li><code>rmdir egg</code> -&gt; try remove it again...</li>\n<li><code>ls</code> -&gt; well, hopefully its gone by now.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Did it work?</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Copy the directory ''chicken'', along with its files, to directory ''fox'' (use the <code>-r</code> option of the <code>cp</code> command).</p>\n<p><code>cp -r CurrentDir NewDir</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Remove directory ''chicken'' without first deleting all its files. Which options must you use to force this to occur without first deleting all the files in directory?</p>\n<p><strong><em>HINT: What option do you use when copying above? Take a look at the steps below..</em></strong></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Use the following command to create file ''allfiles'' which shows all the files in all the subdirectories of playarea:</p>\n<p><code>ls -al * &gt; allfiles</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Now, mail the ''allfiles'' file to the class email:</p>\n<p><code>mail cop3014.lab@gmail.com &lt; allfiles</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>To turn off journaling, using the exit command:</p>\n<p><code>exit</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>Submit ''allfiles'' and ''session_log'' to the Submission Repository.\n<p><code>FSsubmit LAB1 allfiles</code></p>\n<p><code>FSsubmit LAB1 session_log</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Verify that your files got into the repository.</p>\n<p><code>FSstatus</code></p>\n</li>\n</ol>', 'tapiwa', '2013-09-04 20:09:21', '2013-09-04 21:09:50', 1),
