INSERT INTO `summer_cpp_template_programs` (`id`, `class_id`, `session_id`, `prog_name`, `type`, `num_tc`, `num_source`, `num_input`, `num_output`, `num_addition`, `s_points`, `d_points`, `e_points`, `c_points`, `late`, `input`, `output`, `stage`, `published`, `description`, `active`, `graded`) VALUES
(1, 7, 2, 'hello_world', 'cpp', 1, 1, 0, 0, 1, 2, 2, 1, 0, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<h4><em><strong>What''s needed</strong></em></h4>\n<p>Last week assignment was given to you where you had to write a program that printed out "Hello world". For we will be giving you a chance to gain some credit for that by submitting that assignment here.</p>\n<h ><span  underline;"><strong>Requirements</strong></span></h4>\n<p>Make sure that you program displays just like the one below does</p>\n<p><code>(c)2013, username firstName lastName</code></p>\n<p><code>Hello world</code></p>\n<p><code>(c)2013, username firstName lastName</code></p>\n<p>Remember to substitue in you username and name in where needed!</p>', 1, 1),
(2, 7, 3, 'area_sphere', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 2, 2, 4, 0, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<div>Write a program, ''<span  #38761d;">areaSphere.cpp</span><span  #6aa84f;">''</span>, that calculate the surface area &nbsp;of a sphere. The program should ask the user for radius and then print the surface area of the sphere. An example of how the output should look is shown in the box below. Take note that when you do your program your output should look identical to this (except for you name and login). For a program template to work with download shell.cpp from the public repository in unix. This will give an outline of the layout and comments needed.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<blockquote>\n<div><code>FPcopy shell.cpp</code></div>\n</blockquote>\n<div>\n<p>Example output for&nbsp;key-areaSphere.run&nbsp;(you can also download and test this yourself):</p>\n</div>\n<blockquote>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n<div><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n<div><code>This program calculates the surface area of a sphere.</code></div>\n<div><code>The value of PI is 3.1415.</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>Enter the radius: 12</code></div>\n<div><code>The area is the sphere is 1809.5.</code></div>\n<div><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n</div>\n</blockquote>', 1, 1),
(3, 7, 3, 'math1', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 2, 2, 6, 0, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<div>Write a C++ program "<span  #38761d;">math1.cpp"</span> that does the following:</div>\n<div><ol>\n<li>Displays the results of the expressions&nbsp;</li>\n<ol>\n<li><code>15 / 4</code></li>\n<li><code>15 % 4</code></li>\n<li><code>15.0 / 4</code></li>\n<li><code>15 / 4.0</code></li>\n<li><code>3.0 * 5.0</code></li>\n<li><code>3.2 / (6.1 + 5)</code></li>\n</ol>\n<li>Prompt user for the radius of a cone, then calculates and displays the volume of the cone.</li>\n<ul>\n<li>find the formula for volume of cone online</li>\n<li>Use&nbsp;<span  #cc0000;">3.14</span> for PI.</li>\n</ul>\n<li>Calculate the value of above manually to verify that the displayed value are correct.</li>\n</ol></div>\n<div>Example output for the program:</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<blockquote>\n<div>\n<div><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>The result of the expression 15/4 is : 3</code></div>\n<div><code>The result of the expression 15%4 is : 3</code></div>\n<div><code>The result of the expression 15.0/4 is : 3.75</code></div>\n<div><code>The result of the expression 15/4.0 is : 3.75</code></div>\n<div><code>The result of the expression 3.0*5.0 is : 15</code></div>\n<div><code>The result of the expression 32/(6.1+5) is : 2.88288</code></div>\n<div><code>Please enter the radius of cone : 12</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>Please enter the height of cone : 10</code></div>\n<div><code>The voulume of the cone is : 1507.2</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n</div>\n</blockquote>', 1, 1),
(4, 7, 3, 'error', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 2, 2, 4, 0, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<div>For this class two of our primary programming tools are Microsoft Visual C++ and Unix. Both these environments have their own C++ compiler with slight differences, though standard operations (like cout, cin, endl, etc.) will work the same.&nbsp;</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>For this exercise you will be required to download a C++ key program with errors in it and work through through all the errors. This can be done in either unix or windows; however, though both environments may show errors when they exist, it usually is more advantageous to use an IDE like Visual Studio to help you work through problems.</div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>First download the program to your computer and open it up in an IDE of your choice (e.g. Visual Studio)</li>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/8106118/error.cpp" target="_blank">error.cpp</a></li>\n</ul>\n<li>Next compile the code at least once before making any changes to see what kind of errors come up. Notice that with each error, a line number should also be included.</li>\n<li>Edit the heading to display the appropriate information (you name, date, etc.)</li>\n<li>Fix all the errors and&nbsp;SUCCESSFULLY&nbsp;compile the program (Use the compile error list if you can&rsquo;t find all the errors on your own)</li>\n<li>Test out the program and see that it functions well enough.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Copy and submit your program online</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>', 1, 1),
(5, 7, 4, 'convert_temp', 'cpp', 3, 1, 0, 0, 1, 2, 2, 5, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<div>write a program convertTemp.cpp that</div>\n<div><ol>\n<li>asks for temperature in Fahrenheit , and converts , displays the temperature in Celsius</li>\n<li>asks for temperature in Celsius , and converts , displays the temperature in Fahrenheit.</li>\n</ol></div>\n<div>Here is a sample of how the program should look:</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<blockquote>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div class="sites-codeblock sites-codesnippet-block">\n<div><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>===========================</code></div>\n<div><code>This program first converts temperature from Fahrenheit to Celsius,</code></div>\n<div><code>and then converts temperature from Celsius to Fahrenheit.</code></div>\n<div><code>===========================</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>Enter a temperature in Fahrenheit : 78</code></div>\n<div><code>The equivalent temperature in Celsius is 25.5556</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>===========================</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>Enter a temperature in Celsius : 25</code></div>\n<div><code>The equivalent temperature in Fahrenheit is 77</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>===========================</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n</div>\n</blockquote>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Once your program works save and submit your work</div>', 1, 1),
(6, 7, 4, 'shop.cpp', 'cpp', 3, 1, 0, 0, 1, 2, 0, 5, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<div>Write a program, shop.cpp to calculate the amount it&rsquo;ll cost for a shopper buying clothes at a supermarket. The shopper is supposed to buy socks, shirts and pants.</div>\n<div>Your program should take notes of the following standards. Socks cost $5, pants cost $15 and shirts cost $20. The program should ask the user for the amount of socks, shirts and pants bought, and should then provide the total cost of the shopping spree.</div>\n<div>Take a look at the sample program below:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n<div><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n<div><code>This program calculates the total cost of goods for the following shopping items</code></div>\n<div><code>----------------</code></div>\n<div><code>Shirts : $20</code></div>\n<div><code>Pants : $15</code></div>\n<div><code>Socks : $5</code></div>\n<div><code>----------------</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>Enter the amount of shirts you bought: 20</code></div>\n<div><code>Enter the amount of pants you bought: 10</code></div>\n<div><code>Enter the amount of socks you bought: 5</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>The total cost of goods is $575</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n</div>\n</blockquote>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Once your program runs as show above, submit you program</div>', 1, 1),
(7, 7, 4, 'gpa.cpp', 'cpp', 3, 1, 0, 0, 1, 2, 0, 5, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<div>Write a program called gpa.cpp that calculates the GPA for students in a semester. Your program is to ask the user to input a name, input the amount of credit hours taken that semester, and the grade point number for that semester. The GPA for the semester is calculated by dividing the grade point number by the amount of credit hours entered by the user. Your program should ask and do the following:</div>\n<div><ol>\n<li>Enter the name of the student</li>\n<ul>\n<li>Store the name in a string variable called name.</li>\n</ul>\n<li>Enter the number of credit hours taken by the student.</li>\n<ul>\n<li>Store the number of credit hours in an integer variable called credit_hours</li>\n</ul>\n<li>Enter the grade point number for the student.</li>\n<ul>\n<li>Store in a float variable called grade_point_number.</li>\n</ul>\n</ol></div>\n<div>Your program should then print the name of the student, the number of credit hours taken and the GPA for the semester.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Remember the formula for GPA is:</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<blockquote>\n<div><code>GPA = grade_point_number/credit_hours</code></div>\n</blockquote>\n<div>Take a look at the sample program below:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<div>\n<div><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>Enter the name of the student: John Doe</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>Enter the number of credit hours taken by the student: 60</code></div>\n<div><code>Enter the grade point number for the student: 225</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>------------------------------------------</code></div>\n<div><code>The name of the student is John Doe</code></div>\n<div><code>The number of credit hours taken was 60</code></div>\n<div><code>The GPA for John Doe was 3.75</code></div>\n<div><code>------------------------------------------</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></div>\n</div>\n</blockquote>\n<div>Save and submit your program once it run exactly as shown above.</div>', 1, 1),
(8, 7, 5, 'format', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 0, 8, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Write a program <code>formatted.cpp</code> that formats some nubers as shown below. In this program we use <code>setw()</code>, <code>setprecision()</code>, <code>setfill()</code>, <code>left</code> align and <code>right</code> align functions in the <code>&lt;iomanip&gt;</code> library to cleanly format numbers.</p>\n<p>You need to declare two constant double numbers in your program ,</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<blockquote><code>const double PI = 3.14159;</code></blockquote>\n</li>\n<li>\n<blockquote><code>const double e = 2.7182818;</code></blockquote>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>First, use the functions above to print out PI in the following formats,</p>\n<ol>\n<li>3.1416</li>\n<li>3.14159</li>\n<li>3.141590000</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Second, the value of mathematical constant e truncated to 50 decimal places is:</p>\n<blockquote>2.71828182845904523536028747135266249775724709369995...</blockquote>\n<p>Your task is to display the value for <strong><em>e</em></strong> in the following formats:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>2.718</li>\n<li>2.71828</li>\n<li>0002.718</li>\n<li>2.7182818000</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Lastly, you will be intracting a little more with the user. Follow these steps below using cin cout and anyother tools you''ve learn''t to get the correct format:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Ask the user for a floating number.</li>\n<li>Divide the number by 7.0 <em>(make sure you have 3 digits after the decimal point in your output.)</em></li>\n<li>Ask the user for an integer, <strong>AND</strong> a character.</li>\n<li>Divide the integer by 7 and print the <em>quotient</em>.</li>\n<li>Print 10 iterations of the character on the same line using <code>setfill</code> imediately after printing the previous item.</li>\n<li>Print the remainder, yet again, without any spaces or line breaks after the previous two steps</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Here is a sample of how the final output should look like:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>3.1416</code><br /> <code>3.14159</code><br /> <code>3.141590000</code><br /><br /> <code>2.718</code><br /> <code>2.71828</code><br /> <code>0002.718</code><br /> <code>2.7182818000</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter a float number: 50.0</code><br /> <code>The result of the float number 50.0000000 divided by 7.0 is 7.143</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter an integer number: 50</code><br /> <code>Enter a character: s</code><br /> <code>The output is: 7ssssssssss1</code><br /><br /> <code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(9, 7, 5, 'enrollment', 'cpp', 1, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 0, 3, 1, 1, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Write a program <code>enrollment.cpp</code> that displays your enrollment data in last semester, using following format: (you don''t need to use your real academic records, use the one we gave you)</p>\n<p>Format : ^ means space. <em>(The spacing must be EXACT for grading purposes)</em></p>\n<blockquote>StudentID^^Firstname^^Lastname^^Prefix^^Number^^Hours^^Grade</blockquote>\n<p>Below are more specifics on how the output should be formatted using the iomanip class</p>\n<table class="table table-striped">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Data</td>\n<td>Student ID</td>\n<td>Firstname</td>\n<td>Lastname</td>\n<td>Prefix</td>\n<td>Number</td>\n<td>Hours</td>\n<td>Grade</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Field width</td>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Alignment</td>\n<td>left</td>\n<td>left</td>\n<td>left</td>\n<td>left</td>\n<td>left</td>\n<td>left</td>\n<td>left</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Here is some example output of how the program should look:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>FALL 2012 COURSES ENROLLED</code><br /> <code>==========================</code><br /><br /> <code>STUDENTID FIRSTNAME LASTNAME PREFIX NUMBER HOURS GRADE </code><br /> <code>========= ========= ======== ====== ====== ===== =====</code><br /> <code>123456789 John Smith COP 3014l 3 A </code><br /> <code>333333333 Pat Brown CIS 3330 3 B </code><br /> <code>987654321 Mary King PHY 2310 4 C </code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Once your output looks exactly like the program above, save and submit " enrollment.cpp ".</p>', 1, 1),
(10, 7, 5, 'pay1', 'cpp', 3, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 0, 8, 1, 1, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Write a program <code>pay1.cpp</code> that calculates and prints out the average pay given the following information:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Total number of weeks worked,</li>\n<li>Average number of hours per week, and</li>\n<li>Pay rate per hour</li>\n</ul>\n<p>As is the point of this lab, you will be using the <code>&lt;iomanip&gt;</code> library to print out all the information within the program. Before we get into any of the gory details here is a sample of how you program should look:</p>\n<hr />\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program prints out the total AVERAGE pay given weeks worked,</code><br /> <code>hours worked and rate. The formula used is:</code><br /><br /> <code>==================================</code><br /> <code>-- PAY = WEEKS * HOURS * RATE --</code><br /> <code>==================================</code><br /><br /> <code>How many weeks of pay are you trying to calculate: 5</code><br /><br /> <code>How many hours do you work a week: 17</code><br /><br /> <code>How much do you make per hour: 25.47</code><br /><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /> <code>AVERAGE PAY REPORT</code><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /> <code>Weeks : 5</code><br /> <code>Hours : 17</code><br /> <code>Rate : 25.47</code><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /> <code>Pay : 2164.95</code><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<hr />\n<p>Ok, as you can see the program above has quite a lot of formatting added into it. Some of the key commands you will need to use in this are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>setw( _ )</code></li>\n<li><code>fixed</code></li>\n<li><code>setfill(ch)</code> - where <code>ch</code> is a character to fill with</li>\n<li><code>left / right</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The format for the report is shown below. The commands you will need on each of the lines are listed on the right side of the code</p>\n<hr />\n<blockquote><code>1 ===================== -&gt; setw(34) ; setfill(''='') -&gt; Lines 1,3,7,9</code><br /> <code>2 AVERAGE PAY REPORT -&gt; setfill('' '') -&gt; Lines 2, 4, 8</code><br /> <code>3 ===================== </code><br /><br /> <code>4 Weeks : 5 -&gt; setw(10) ; left THEN ''colon'' THEN setw(10) ; right -&gt; Lines 4,5,6,8</code><br /> <code>5 Hours : 17</code><br /> <code>6 Rate : 25.47</code><br /><br /> <code>7 =====================</code><br /> <code>8 Pay : 2164.95</code><br /> <code>9 =====================</code><br /><br /></blockquote>\n<hr />\n<p>Example for setfill:</p>\n<blockquote><code>cout&lt;&lt;setfill(''='') &lt;&lt;setw(34) &lt;&lt; "=" &lt;&lt; endl ;</code> </blockquote>\n<p>Once you program looks exactly like the sample above save and submit you work</p>', 1, 1),
(11, 7, 6, 'grades1', 'cpp', 6, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 6, 1, 1, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>This program is intended to be a starter program to conditional statements. It is designed just to give you a feel of how <code>if-elseif-else<code> conditional stements work</code></code></p>\n<p>Write a program <code>grades1.cpp</code> that displays a percentage range given a specific letter grade. The program should follow these steps</p>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<li>Prompts users for a <code>char</code> grade such as A, B, C, D and F.</li>\n<li>Print out corresponding grade range using the <code>if-elseif-else</code> conditional structure.</li>\n<li>If the user enters anything other than A,B,C,D,F, your program should print "<code>invalid grade</code>". <em>You can use the <code>else</code> construct for this.</em></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<h4><em><strong>Sample output 1:</strong></em></h4>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourlogin yourfirstname yourlastname</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter a letter grade (such as A,B,C,D,F): A</code><br /> <code>Your total points is between 90 and 100.</code></blockquote>\n<h4><em><strong>Sample output 2:</strong></em></h4>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourlogin yourfirstname yourlastname</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter a letter grade (such as A,B,C,D,F): B</code><br /> <code>Your total points is between 80 and 90.</code></blockquote>\n<h4><em><strong>Sample output 3:</strong></em></h4>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourlogin yourfirstname yourlastname</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter a letter grade (such as A,B,C,D,F): C</code><br /> <code>Your total points is between 70 and 80.</code></blockquote>\n<h4><em><strong>Sample output 4:</strong></em></h4>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourlogin yourfirstname yourlastname</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter a letter grade (such as A,B,C,D,F): D</code><br /> <code>Your total points is between 60 and 70.</code></blockquote>\n<h4><em><strong>Sample output 5:</strong></em></h4>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourlogin yourfirstname yourlastname</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter a letter grade (such as A,B,C,D,F): F</code><br /> <code>You have failed the class.</code></blockquote>\n<h4><em><strong>Sample output 6:</strong></em></h4>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourlogin yourfirstname yourlastname</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter a letter grade (such as A,B,C,D,F): a</code><br /> <code>Invalid grade.</code></blockquote>\n<p>As you can see, this program is case sensetive and any invalid input should give an <code>Invalid grade</code> error.</p>', 1, 1),
(12, 7, 6, 'sound_waves', 'cpp', 5, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 0, 13, 1, 1, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Write a program <code>sound_waves.cpp</code> that finds the time it takes for sound to travel through different materials. The general formula for calculating time gives the speed and distance is:</p>\n<blockquote><code>Time = Distance / Speed</code></blockquote>\n<p>Your program should display a menu giving some basic details on what the conversion rates are as well as the necessary options that are available for the user to input. After that some prompts should be given and final calculation of the time should be done. Follow the steps below:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<h4>Basic Info and the Menu</h4>\nFirst thing you need to do is display any basic program information for the user to see and then display the menu as needed. This should be a couple of <code>cout</code> statements with the use of <code>iomanip</code>, so nothing extraordinary should been needed. The formatting for the menu will follow this structure\n<ul>\n<li>First letter with width (<code>setw</code>) of 6, aligned to the left (<code>left</code>)</li>\n<li>Option item (e.g. air) will have a width of 8, aligned to the left</li>\n<li>Finally a single space and then the units printed out as &lsquo;m/s&rsquo;</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h4>Prompt for the type</h4>\nAfter the menu is displayed, a prompt should be given asking the user to pick an option from the menu. At this point you should be thinking a bit about &ldquo;<code>data validation</code>&rdquo; and making sure that the user entered the correct data. So suppose that anything other than the option is entered your program needs to be able to detect this error and exit the program as needed. Both uppercase AND lowercase should be acceptable (Check out the sample programs below).</li>\n<li>\n<h4>Prompt for the distance</h4>\nThe next part will entail asking the user for the distance they are trying to convert. Yet again, more validation needs to be done so we make sure that no funky numbers are being entered. Here we need to make sure that the distance isn&rsquo;t negative, non-numeric or <em>funky<em>. <br /> </em></em></li>\n<li>\n<h4>Find the answer and display</h4>\nNow comes the conditional statements that we use to evaluate the users option and print out the response. At this point you need to take the prompted type that the user entered and either use <code>if-else</code> statements or a <code>switch</code> statement to calculate an answer. This is entirely personal preference but the end result should still be the same. Also take not of the formating of the final result as it does need <code>iomanip</code> to be come out just right.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Here are a couple of sample programs to show you how the program should run <span  #300000;">(Note: to keep this short I will display all repetive non-essiential material ONLY ONCE)</span></p>\n<h4>Sample 1: Invalid option entry</h4>\n<blockquote><code>========================================</code><br /> <code>Welcome to Sound Wave Calulator</code><br /> <code>========================================</code><br /> <br /> <code>This calculator will help you figure out how long</code><br /> <code>it would take for sound to travel through different</code><br /> <code>mediums.</code><br /> <br /> <code>----------------------------------------</code><br /> <code>===&gt; Sound Wave Menu</code><br /> <code>----------------------------------------</code><br /> <code>A Air 345 m/s</code><br /> <code>R Rubber 60 m/s</code><br /> <code>G Gold 3240 m/s</code><br /> <code>C Copper 4600 m/s</code><br /> <code>----------------------------------------</code><br /> <br /> <code>Select the medium the sound wave will travel through: z</code><br /> <code>Sorry I don''t recognize that option!</code><br /> <code>Goodbye!</code></blockquote>\n<hr />\n<h4>Sample 2: Invalid numeric entry</h4>\n<blockquote><code>Select the medium the sound wave will travel through: a</code><br /><br /> <code>Please enter in the distance: -200</code><br /><br /> <code>Sorry but it looks like the distance is off, please check it and try again.</code><br /> <code>Goodbye!</code></blockquote>\n<h4>Sample 3: Proper Entry</h4>\n<blockquote><code>Select the medium the sound wave will travel through: r</code><br /><br /> <code>Please enter in the distance: 5321</code><br /><br /> <code>The time it takes to travel 5321m in rubber is 88.68s</code><br /> <code>The conversion rate is 60.00 m/s</code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(13, 7, 6, 'quadratic', 'cpp', 4, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 0, 8, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>For this assignment you will be writing a quadratic root calculator. The general quadratic equation follows as:</p>\n<blockquote><code>a*x^2 + b*x + c = 0</code></blockquote>\n<p>In a lot of problems, naturally we would like to find the roots (or solutions) to quadratic formulas for some reason or the other. Some simple example include projectiles much like throwing balls or propelling missiles, even in areas like economics where they can be used to calculate profit given some quadratic economic function.</p>\n<h4><strong><em>Finding roots</em></strong></h4>\n<p>So given the formula above we can find the 2 roots for the quadratic formula using the following formula</p>\n<p><img  block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" src="http://www.biology.arizona.edu/biomath/tutorials/quadratic/images/rootseqn5.gif" alt="quadratic roots" width="295" height="139" /></p>\n<p>As you can see quadratic equations tend to have 2 roots and at times, due to the square root some of these roots can be <strong>complex</strong> (or <strong>imaginary</strong>). This is due to the fact that the square root of a negative number just doesn''t exist so in our program we have to account for this. This can be done using some conditional statements and tweaking the way we do our calculations.</p>\n<p>To actually check if the roots are negative we only need to focus on what&rsquo;s inside the square root, the <strong><em>discriminant</em></strong>. This should look something like:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(b*b) - 4*a*c</code></blockquote>\n<p>Given this we can determine whether or not the roots will be complex or not. Check out the psuedocode below:</p>\n<blockquote><ol>\n<li>\n<h4><em><strong>Gather info</strong></em></h4>\nFirst gather all your coefficients, a, b and c and store them in variables</li>\n<li>\n<h4><em><strong>Condition for the discriminant </strong></em></h4>\nStart checking the <em>discriminant<em> using an if statement, kinda like this:<br /> <code>if ( (b*b) - 4*a*c) &lt; 0</code> </em></em></li>\n<li>\n<h4><em><strong>True for discriminant </strong></em></h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Find real part for the root\n<blockquote><code>-b / (2*a)</code></blockquote>\n</li>\n<li>Find Complex part of the root. <br />For this part since the discriminant is negative you will have to take the absolute value then take the square root after. So it should look like this :\n<blockquote><code>sqrt(abs((b*b) - 4*a*c)) / (2*a)</code></blockquote>\n</li>\n<li>Print out the final results with a bit of formatting (i.e. <code>fixed</code> and <code>setprecision</code> to get only 3 decimal places).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h4><em><strong>True for discriminant </strong></em></h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Find first root</li>\n<li>Find second root</li>\n<li>Print out the final results with a bit of formatting(<em>use the same formatting as before<em>)</em></em></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h4><em><strong>Done!</strong></em></h4>\nTerminate the program as needed</li>\n</ol></blockquote>\n<p>Check out the samples below</p>\n<h4><strong>Sample 1: Complex roots</strong></h4>\n<blockquote><code>=======================================</code><br /> <code> Quadratic Formula Calculator</code><br /> <code>=======================================</code><br /><br /> <code>Input quadratic coefficient for ax^2 + bx + c = 0</code><br /> <code>a = 1</code><br /> <code>b = 4</code><br /> <code>c = 8</code><br /><br /> <code>---------------------------------------</code><br /><br /> <code>This equation has complex roots in it.</code><br /><br /> <code>root1 = -2.000+2.000i</code><br /> <code>root2 = -2.000-2.000i</code><br /><br /> <code>---------------------------------------</code><br /><br /> <code>Program terminated.</code><br /><br /> <code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin firstName lastName</code></blockquote>\n<h4><strong>Sample 2: Regular roots</strong></h4>\n<blockquote><code>=======================================</code><br /> <code> Quadratic Formula Calculator</code><br /> <code>=======================================</code><br /><br /> <code>Input quadratic coefficient for ax^2 + bx + c = 0</code><br /> <code>a = 1</code><br /> <code>b = 4</code><br /> <code>c = 4</code><br /><br /> <code>---------------------------------------</code><br /><br /> <code>This equation is a regular quadratic equation.</code><br /><br /> <code>root1 = -2</code><br /> <code>root2 = -2</code><br /><br /> <code>---------------------------------------</code><br /><br /> <code>Program terminated.</code><br /><br /> <code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin firstName lastName</code></blockquote>\n<p>Once you are done save and submit your work</p>', 1, 1),
(14, 7, 7, 'calcMenu', 'cpp', 5, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 6, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<h4><strong><em>Refresher for last weeks programs</em></strong></h4>\n<p>Write a program <code>calcMenu.cpp</code> that lets the user perform arithmetic operations on two numbers. Your program must be menu driven, allowing the user to select the operation (+, -, *, or /) and input the numbers.</p>\n<p>The program should ask the user for a menu option, then ask the user 2 numbers to operate on. Finally it should evaluate the following options using a switch statement:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>add</li>\n<li>subtract</li>\n<li>multiply</li>\n<li>divide</li>\n</ol>\n<p>An example of how the program should work given a correct option is shown below.</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program is a menu driven program that does some calculations</code><br /> <code>and prints out the result as needed.</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code> MENU</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code>1: Add</code><br /> <code>2: Subtract</code><br /> <code>3: Multiply</code><br /> <code>4: Divide</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code>Enter your choice: 2</code><br /> <code>Enter two numbers: 23 45</code><br /> <code>Difference -22</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p><strong>If an option that isn&rsquo;t available the program should display &ldquo;Invalid input&rdquo; error and exit out. Here is an example of how it should look: </strong></p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program is a menu driven program that does some calculations</code><br /> <code>and prints out the result as needed.</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code> MENU</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code>1: Add</code><br /> <code>2: Subtract</code><br /> <code>3: Multiply</code><br /> <code>4: Divide</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code>Enter your choice: 32</code><br /> <code>Invalid input</code><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Once you have completed the program, save and submit you program.</p>', 1, 1),
(15, 7, 7, 'five_floats', 'cpp', 2, 1, 1, 0, 2, 1, 1, 3, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>For this program you will be required to make use of files and the <code>fstream</code> class. To be more specific you will be dealing with input files.</p>\n<p>Write a program <code>fiveFloats.cpp</code> that follows the following steps</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Opens a files <code>numbers.txt</code></li>\n<li>Read in 5 numbers and store them in variables</li>\n<li>Find the sum, product and average of these 5 numbers</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Check out the example below to see how exactly this programs should operate:</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>For the numbers <code>3.5, 4.5, 12.0, 7.9, 5</code> we get the following:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code> Five Floats from a file</code><br /> <code>This program does the following:</code><br /> <code>1) opens a file that contains 5 float numbers</code><br /> <code>2) reads in the 5 numbers</code><br /> <code>3) calculate the sum, product and average</code><br /> <code>4) prints out the results.</code><br /><br /> <code>The sum of the five float numbers is 32.9</code><br /> <code>The product of the five float numbers is 7465.5</code><br /> <code>The average of the five float numbers is 6.58</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Should the file fail to open the program should print the following message and exit out immediately. This can be done using a a conditional statement like this:</p>\n<div><code>File could not open!</code></div>\n<p>Once your program is done save and submit your work.</p>', 1, 1),
(16, 7, 7, 'employee1', 'cpp', 2, 1, 1, 1, 3, 1, 2, 8, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>The purpose of this program is to try and gain a better understanding fo how to use both input and output files within you''re program. Realistically as files are a large part of today''s compuational arena it will become important to understand how multiple sources of data can be used.</p>\n<p><em><strong>Note:</strong></em> You are advised to write this program locally on your computer and then submitting here once you are done.</p>\n<p>Write a program <code>employee1.cpp</code> that handles an input file, <code>input.txt</code>, and an output file , <code>output.txt</code>. The file should peform the following functions:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Check if the files are open or not using the .fail() or .is_open() commands. If this fails exit the program as shown below</li>\n<li>Read in the three employee records from input.txt and display them to the screen</li>\n<li>Close input.txt using the .close() feature</li>\n<li>Use cin to read in an employee record</li>\n<li>Save to file output.txt</li>\n<li>Close the file output.txt</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Here is a sample <code>input.txt</code> file:</p>\n<blockquote>King Tallahassee FL 32311<br /> Wang Chicago IL 45600<br /> Brown SouthBend IN 46323</blockquote>\n<p>Here is a sample of how the program should run:</p>\n<h4><strong><em>Sample 1: Should the files fail to open</em></strong></h4>\n<blockquote><code>A file could not be opened! Terminating!</code></blockquote>\n<h4><strong><em>Sample 2: Correct execution of the program</em></strong></h4>\n<blockquote><code>=============================================</code><br /> <code>Reading in from input.txt</code><br /> <code>=============================================</code><br /> <code>Employee name is King</code><br /> <code>City is Tallahassee</code><br /> <code>State is FL</code><br /> <code>Zipcode is 32311</code><br /><br /> <code>Employee name is Wang</code><br /> <code>City is Chicago</code><br /> <code>State is IL</code><br /> <code>Zipcode is 45600</code><br /><br /> <code>Employee name is Brown</code><br /> <code>City is SouthBend</code><br /> <code>State is IN</code><br /> <code>Zipcode is 46323</code><br /><br /> <code>=============================================</code><br /> <code>Now writing to output.txt.</code><br /> <code>=============================================</code><br /> <code>Please enter in information below:</code><br /> <code>Please enter the new employee''s lastname : Doe</code><br /> <code>Please enter the city the new employee lives : Tallahassee</code><br /> <code>Please enter the state : FL</code><br /> <code>Please enter the zipcode : 32307</code><br /><br /> <code>Data written to file... exiting</code><br /> <code>------------------------------------</code></blockquote>\n<p>Once you are done save and submit your work.</p>', 1, 1),
(17, 7, 7, 'pay2', 'cpp', 3, 1, 0, 1, 2, 2, 2, 5, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>For this part of lab you will be writing a program that writes output to console AND also to a file.</p>\n<p>Write a program <code>pay2.cpp</code> that:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Reads in\n<ul>\n<li>the number of weeks worked,</li>\n<li>number of hours worked per week, and</li>\n<li>the rate at which the employee is paid.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Calculate the average pay based on these inputs</li>\n<li>Print to the file <code>pay2.out</code> and to the console</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Check out the examples below</p>\n<h4>Console output:</h4>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program prints out the total AVERAGE pay given weeks worked,</code><br /> <code>hours worked and rate. The formula used is:</code><br /> <code>==================================</code><br /> <code>-- PAY = WEEKS * HOURS * RATE --</code><br /> <code>==================================</code><br /> <code>How many weeks of pay are you trying to calculate: 5</code><br /> <code>How many hours do you work a week: 17</code><br /> <code>How much do you make per hour: 25.47</code><br /><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /> <code>AVERAGE PAY REPORT</code><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /> <code>Weeks : 5</code><br /> <code>Hours : 17</code><br /> <code>Rate : 25.47</code><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /> <code>Pay : 2164.95</code><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<h4>File output : <code>pay2.out</code></h4>\n<blockquote><code>=====================</code><br /> <code>AVERAGE PAY REPORT</code><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /> <code>Weeks : 5</code><br /> <code>Hours : 17</code><br /> <code>Rate : 25.47</code><br /> <code>=====================</code><br /> <code>Pay : 2164.95</code><br /> <code>=====================</code></blockquote>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> the exact same report is written to the file <code>pay2.out</code>. In order to do this, you just have to duplicate print statements, and redirect them to file using outFile. Here is an example showing how they work:</p>\n<blockquote><code>cout &lt;&lt; &ldquo;--- This is a sample ---&rdquo; &lt;&lt; endl;</code><br /> <code>outFile &lt;&lt; &ldquo;--- This is a sample ---&rdquo; &lt;&lt; endl;</code></blockquote>\n<p>This would print the exact same line to the screen AND to file!</p>\n<p>Once you have completed this, save and submit your file below</p>', 1, 1),
(18, 7, 8, 'gas1', 'cpp', 3, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 6, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Write a program <code>gas1.cpp</code>&nbsp;that calculates the price of gas used by a car. The program should ask the user for mileage AND options of whether the car is an Economy car or a Gas Guzzler.</p>\n<p>The relative prices for gas are</p>\n<ul>\n<li>$0.25 per mile for Economy cars</li>\n<li>$0.35 per mile for Gas Guzzlers</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Once these inputs have been entered, the program should calculate the total price for the mileage and display it. Some example of the program should run are shown below:</p>\n<h4><strong><em>For Option 1:</em></strong></h4>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>How many miles have you travelled: 512</code><br /><br /> <code>What kind of car do you have: </code><br /> <code>Enter == 1 for Ec OR == 2 for Gas Guzzler == : 1</code><br /><br /> <code>You have an Economy Car</code><br /> <code>Total price is: 128</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<h4><strong><em>For Option 2:</em></strong></h4>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>How many miles have you travelled: 847</code><br /><br /> <code>What kind of car do you have: </code><br /> <code>Enter == 1 for Ec OR == 2 for Gas Guzzler == : 2</code><br /><br /> <code>You have a Gas Guzzler</code><br /> <code>Total price is: 296.45</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<h4><strong><em>For anything else</em></strong></h4>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> If the options entered are anything other than the ones entered, your program should display the error message &ldquo;Invalid Type!&rdquo; and exit out of the program. An example can be shown below:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>How many miles have you travelled: 235.5</code><br /><br /> <code>What kind of car do you have: </code><br /> <code>Enter == 1 for Ec OR == 2 for Gas Guzzler == : 3</code><br /><br /> <code>Invalid Type</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Save and submit you file.</p>', 1, 1),
(19, 7, 8, 'merge1', 'cpp', 2, 1, 2, 1, 4, 1, 2, 6, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>For this exercise we will be taking a closer look at files. The goal of this assignment is to essentially make use of reading from INPUT streams as well as writing to an OUTPUT stream within the same program.</p>\n<p>Before you get started you will need to download the 2 input files <code>merge1.txt</code> and <code>merge2.txt</code> from the public repository on this website. <code>merge1.txt</code> contains a list of 3 first-names and <code>merge2.txt</code> contains a list of 3 grades. (you can also create these in notepad).</p>\n<p>Once you have these 2 files write a program <code>merge.cpp</code> that reads in all the data from these two files and prints a result to the file <code>users.txt</code> and to the console (using <code>cout</code>).</p>\n<p>Sample algorithm is shown below</p>\n<ol>\n<li>&lt;&lt;&lt; #include .... &gt;&gt;&gt;</li>\n<li>Open merge1.txt - ifstream and merge2.txt</li>\n<li>Open user.txt - ofstream</li>\n<li>Check to see that these files are open</li>\n<li>Read in data from merge1.txt and merge2.txt</li>\n<li>Print result to <code>cout</code></li>\n<li>Print result to <code>user.txt</code> (just duplicate what comes out on <code>cout</code>)</li>\n<li>&lt;&lt;&lt; return 0 ..... &gt;&gt;&gt;</li>\n</ol>\n<p>A sample of program execution is shown below. (This output is in both <code>COUT</code> and the FILE <code>users.txt</code></p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program opens up the file merge1.txt(names) and</code><br /> <code>merge2.txt(grades). Once open the files will combine</code><br /> <code>the data to follow the form:</code><br /> <code>========================================</code><br /> <code>Student Num: Name grade</code><br /> <code>========================================</code><br /> <code>Student 1: John 100</code><br /> <code>Student 2: Leslie 75</code><br /> <code>Student 3: Cole 96</code><br /> <code>========================================</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Remember to use <code></code> to make sure that your output is formatted properly. The following properties should be used with <code>iomanip</code>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>For the ''student'' part just print is out verbose.</li>\n<li>For the name use a <code>setw(15)</code> after printing the student info.</li>\n<li>For the final grade, simply append this last bit after the name.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Once you are done save and submit your work.</p>', 1, 1),
(20, 7, 9, 'calcMenu1', 'cpp', 3, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 8, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>For this exercise you will be modifying a program <code>calcMenu.cpp</code> that you (should have) created back in Lab 6. Copy/Download calcMenu.cpp as calcMenu1.cpp and use it to complete this lab.</p>\n<p>Once you have downloaded it over you will need to add in a <code>do-while</code> loop and a couple of extra lines in your switch statement to get it to keep running until an exit key is entered (Look at examples below to see the differences).</p>\n<p>Your original program ( <code>calcMenu.cpp</code> ) should look like this:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program is a menu driven program that does some calculations</code><br /> <code>and prints out the result as needed.</code><br /><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code> MENU</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code>1: Add</code><br /> <code>2: Subtract</code><br /> <code>3: Multiply</code><br /> <code>4: Divide</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter your choice: 2</code><br /> <code>Enter two numbers: 23 45</code><br /> <code>Difference -22</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>After adding the <code>do-while</code> loop the program should look like this:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /> <code>This program is a menu driven program that does some calculations</code><br /> <code>and prints out the result as needed.</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code> MENU</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code>1: Add</code><br /> <code>2: Subtract</code><br /> <code>3: Multiply</code><br /> <code>4: Divide</code><br /> <code>5: Exit</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code>Enter your choice: 1</code><br /> <code>Enter two numbers: 23 4</code><br /> <code>Sum 27</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code> MENU</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code>1: Add</code><br /> <code>2: Subtract</code><br /> <code>3: Multiply</code><br /> <code>4: Divide</code><br /> <code>5: Exit</code><br /> <code>==========</code><br /> <code>Enter your choice: 5</code><br /> <code>************************</code><br /> <code>Closing Program!</code><br /> <code>************************</code><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Once you have completed the program save and submit your program.</p>', 1, 1),
(21, 7, 9, 'starSquare', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 0, 3, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>In this part of lab you will have to write a program <code>starSquare.cpp</code> that uses nested for loops (fancy way of saying a loop inside a loop). This program first asks users for an integer as the size of a square, and then prints out a square of stars using two for loops ( i.e. the two for loops are nested).</p>\n<p>Here is an example, if the users type the number 10 at the prompt, your program should print a 10 x 10 square of stars like this:</p>\n<blockquote>* * * * * * * * * *<br /> * * * * * * * * * *<br /> * * * * * * * * * *<br /> * * * * * * * * * *<br /> * * * * * * * * * *<br /> * * * * * * * * * *<br /> * * * * * * * * * *<br /> * * * * * * * * * *<br /> * * * * * * * * * *<br /> * * * * * * * * * *</blockquote>\n<p>Here is an example of the actual output:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, youUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>Please enter the number of stars on the side of the square: 5</code><br /><br /> <code>* * * * *</code><br /> <code>* * * * *</code><br /> <code>* * * * *</code><br /> <code>* * * * *</code><br /> <code>* * * * *</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, youUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Once you have completed the program submit your program</p>', 1, 1),
(22, 7, 9, 'fileNumberStats', 'cpp', 3, 1, 1, 0, 2, 1, 3, 10, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Write a program <code>readNums.cpp</code> that reads data from a file and prints out information based on the contents of the file. Your program should read from the file <code>readNums.in</code>. The file will contain a list of integers; positive and negative. Your program should read each integer in the file using a<code> while</code> loop and display the following information:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The total and sum of the numbers</li>\n<li>The number of odd integers</li>\n<li>The number of even integers</li>\n<li>The sum of positive integers</li>\n<li>The sum of negative integers</li>\n<li>The average of positive integers</li>\n<li>The average of negative integers</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For the <code>readNums.in</code> file you may create a file containing random positive and negative numbers to test your program.</p>\n<p>Take a look at how the final result should look like below:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>Statistics for the file ''readNums.in''.</code><br /><br /> <code>============================================</code><br /> <code>Report for readNums.in</code><br /> <code>============================================</code><br /> <code> Total Number of ints : 76</code><br /> <code> Total Sum of ints : 3544</code><br /> <code>---------------------------------------------</code><br /> <code> Number of Even ints : 42</code><br /> <code> Number of Odd ints : 24</code><br /> <code> Number of Pos ints : 57</code><br /> <code> Number of Neg ints : 19</code><br /> <code>---------------------------------------------</code><br /> <code> Sum of Pos ints : 16176</code><br /> <code> Sum of Neg ints : -12632</code><br /> <code>---------------------------------------------</code><br /> <code> Avg of Pos ints : 283.789</code><br /> <code> Avg of Neg ints : -664.842</code><br /> <code>=============================================</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Take note that this program does use <code>iomanip</code>. The first column uses width formation(<code>setw</code>) of 25 spaces.</p>\n<p>Once you have completed the program submit your program.</p>', 1, 1);
INSERT INTO `summer_cpp_template_programs` (`id`, `class_id`, `session_id`, `prog_name`, `type`, `num_tc`, `num_source`, `num_input`, `num_output`, `num_addition`, `s_points`, `d_points`, `e_points`, `c_points`, `late`, `input`, `output`, `stage`, `published`, `description`, `active`, `graded`) VALUES
(26, 7, 10, 'extract', 'cpp', 3, 1, 1, 1, 3, 1, 2, 6, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>The purpose of this program is to find a code from a list of numbers. These numbers are from 0 - 9, and after each number is a space in the file. Your job is to extract a special code containing only 10 of those numbers. For the number to be part of the code, it should be divisible by 2. After extracting 10 numbers divisible by 2 for the code, write those 10 numbers to the file to form the expected code.</p>\n<p>A sample of the input file &#40;which is called "<code>question.txt</code>"&#41; looks like this.</p>\n<blockquote><code> 4 9 4 3 5 7 8 1 9 2 5 1 4 5 8 9 1 3 6 9 2 8 6 2 9 8 4 3 2 7 1 8 6 4 5 7 </code></blockquote>\n<p>The output file &#40;which should be called "<code>code.txt</code>"&#41; looks like this.</p>\n<blockquote><code> 4482486286 </code></blockquote>\n<p>You should also print the message onto the console.</p>\n<blockquote><code> The code has been printed to the file </code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(27, 7, 10, 'letterCount', 'cpp', 2, 1, 1, 0, 2, 1, 2, 5, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>The purpose of this program is to read through a file that contains a lot of letters (characters, if you will). Your job is to write code that reads in each character from the file, and parse it to see whether it''s a vowel or a consonant.</p>\n<p>Your program should then display to the console, the number of vowels and the number of consonants.</p>\n<p>The name of the file is called "<code>input.txt</code>", and your output should look something like this.</p>\n<blockquote><code>Opening file and reading the letters...</code><br /><br /> <code>There are 14 vowels</code><br /> <code>There are 32 consonants</code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(28, 7, 10, 'pancakes', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 8, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<h4><strong>Pancake Glutton</strong></h4>\n<p>Requires:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>variables, data types, and numerical operators</li>\n<li>basic input/output</li>\n<li>logic (if statements, switch statements)</li>\n<li>loops (for, while, do-while)</li>\n<li>arrays</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Write a program that asks the user to enter the number of pancakes eaten for breakfast by 10 different contestants (Contestant 1, Contestant 2, ..., Contestant 10)</p>\n<p>Once the data has been entered the program must analyze the data and output who ate the most and least pancakes during the contest.</p>\n<p>Here is how the output should look:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>== Pancake Glutton C </code><br /><br /> <code>Let''s see who ate the least and most pancakes!</code><br /><br /> <code>Enter in all the contestants numbers:</code><br /><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 1 eat: 4</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 2 eat: 8</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 3 eat: 5</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 4 eat: 5</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 5 eat: 7</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 6 eat: 9</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 7 eat: 4</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 8 eat: 3</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 9 eat: 2</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 10 eat: 10</code><br /><br /> <code>Contestant 9 ate the least pancakes!</code><br /> <code>Contestant 10 ate the most pancakes!</code><br /><br /> <code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(29, 7, 11, 'pancake_rounds', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 8, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Remember pancakes from last? Well for this program you will be modify your original pancakes so that our competition could have a little more flexibility and make better use of our array.</p>\n<p>Here are some of the major changes you will need to make:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Increase the size of your original array to 100 (We make it large because we don''t know how many contestants there will be. Better having too many than not enough)</li>\n<li>Have a prompt that asks the user for how many contestants there are</li>\n<li>Find the min and max given the number of contestants</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Check out the sample program below:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>== Pancake Glutton C </code><br /><br /> <code>Let''s see who ate the least and most pancakes!</code><br /><br /> <code>How many contestants were there: 3</code><br /> <code>Enter in all the contestants numbers:</code><br /><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 1 eat: 1</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 2 eat: 8</code><br /> <code>How many pancakes did contestant 3 eat: 5</code><br /><br /> <code>Contestant 1 ate the least pancakes!</code><br /> <code>Contestant 2 ate the most pancakes!</code><br /> <code>There were 3 contestants in this round!</code><br /><br /> <code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(30, 7, 11, 'reverse', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 6, 1, 4, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Write a program reverseNumbers.cpp that asks the user for 15 integers and prints those 15 integers in natural order and then reverse order.</p>\n<p>For simplicity, it would be best if you used <code>loops</code> and <code>arrays</code> both to read in all the data as well as print out that data.</p>\n<p>Check the sample below:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013 yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program reverses 15 numbers.</code><br /><br /> <code>=======================================</code><br /> <code>Please enter in 15 numbers: </code><br /> <code>46 545 465 654 321 87 312 687 489 987 684 78 91 658 365</code><br /> <code>=======================================</code><br /> <code>The numbers in order: </code><br /> <code>46 545 465 654 321 87 312 687 489 987 684 78 91 658 365 </code><br /> <code>---------------------------------------</code><br /> <code>The numbers in reverse: </code><br /> <code>365 658 91 78 684 987 489 687 312 87 321 654 465 545 46 </code><br /> <code>=======================================</code><br /><br /> <code>(c)2013 yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(31, 7, 11, 'grade_report', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 8, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>For this program you will be dealing with parallel array (i.e. 2 arrays whose records match based on the index of each item).</p>\n<p>Write a program that takes in the grades and names of 10 students in the class. Your program should use an array of floats and Strings for the data types. Your program should then print a report based on the grades given by the user - this report should contain the following</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The name of the student with the highest grade and the grade that he or she got.</li>\n<li>The name of the student with the lowest grade, as well as the grade that he or she got.</li>\n<li>The average of all the grades in the class.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Check out a sample of how the program should run below</p>\n<blockquote><code>Please enter the student name and the grade he or she got</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: john</code><br /> <code>Grade: 100</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: jake</code><br /> <code>Grade: 99</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: jill</code><br /> <code>Grade: 98</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: jude</code><br /> <code>Grade: 97</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: jack</code><br /> <code>Grade: 96</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: james</code><br /> <code>Grade: 95</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: jonathan</code><br /> <code>Grade: 94</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: jah</code><br /> <code>Grade: 93</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: jimm</code><br /> <code>Grade: 92</code><br /><br /> <code>Name: drake</code><br /> <code>Grade: 91</code><br /><br /> <code>john has the highest grade of 100</code><br /> <code>drake has the lowest grade of 91</code><br /> <code>The average of all the grades is 95.5</code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(32, 7, 12, 'round', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 7, 1, 3, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>An extremely useful programming algorithm for rounding a real number to n decimal places is shown in the step below:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>multiply the number by 10^n</li>\n<li>add 0.5</li>\n<li>delete the fractional part of the result</li>\n<li>divide by 10^n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>for example, using this algorithm to round the number 78.374625 to three decimal places yields:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>78.374625 * 10^3 = 78374.625</li>\n<li>78374.625 + 0.5 = 78375.125</li>\n<li>retaining the integer part = 78375</li>\n<li>78375 divide by 10^3 = 78.375</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Use this information to write C++ function name <code>round()</code> that rounds the value of its first parameter to the number of decimal places specified by its second parameter.</p>\n<blockquote><code>double round(double, int ); </code> // function prototype</blockquote>\n<p>The <code>main()</code> function of your program <code>round.cpp</code> asks user for a double number to be rounded and an integer that specify the decimal places, calls the <code>round()</code> function , and print out the rounded number to screen.</p>\n<p>Here is a sample of how the output should look:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last <code>This program rounds off the a number to a specific number</code><br /> <code>of decimal places</code><br /><br /> <code>Please enter a double number to be rounded: 12.3265448674</code><br /><br /> <code>Please enter an integer number to specify the decimal places: 2</code><br /><br /> <code>The number 12.3265 rounded to 2 decimal places is : 12.33</code><br /><br /> <code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code> </code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(33, 7, 12, 'min_max', 'cpp', 2, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 6, 1, 2, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Write a program min_max.cpp that find the min and the max of 3 given numbers. The program will contain 2 function prototypes</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<blockquote><code>int getMin(int a, int b, int c);</code></blockquote>\n<ul>\n<li>This function will find the minimum value of the numbers entered by the user. Once the minimum value is found, it should return it back to the main function.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<blockquote><code>int getMax(int a, int b, int c);</code></blockquote>\n<ul>\n<li>This function will find the maximum value of the numbers entered by the user. Once the maximum value is found, it should return it back to the main function.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Take a look at the sample code below to see an example of how the final product should run.</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, youUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program calculates the min and max for 3 prompted numbers.</code><br /><br /> <code>Input three integer values and hit return.</code><br /> <code>1 5 89</code><br /><br /> <code>The minimum value of 1, 5, and 89 is: 1.</code><br /> <code>The maximum value of 1, 5, and 89 is: 89.</code><br /><br /> <code>(c)2013, youUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(34, 7, 12, 'combinations', 'cpp', 4, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 16, 1, 4, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>When we want to find the number of combinations of size 2 without repeated letters that can be made from the three letters in the word CAT, order doesn''t matter; AT is the same as TA. We can write out the three combinations of size two that can be taken from this set of size three:</p>\n<blockquote><code>CA CT AT</code></blockquote>\n<p>We say ''3 choose 2'' and write 3_C_2. Similarly we can use a formula to calculate the combinations <code>n_C_k</code> is:</p>\n<blockquote><code>n!</code><br /> <code>----------</code><br /> <code>k!(n - k)!</code></blockquote>\n<p>For our CAT example, we do the following: <code>3_C_2</code></p>\n<blockquote><code>3_C_2</code><br /><br /> <code  5em;">= 3! / 2!(1!)</code><br /> <code  5em;">= (3*2*1) / (2*1) * (1) = 6 / 2 = 3</code><br /> <code  5em;">= 6 / 2 = 3</code><br /> <code  5em;">= 3</code></blockquote>\n<h3>What you need to do</h3>\n<p>Download this shell program &lsquo;combinations.cpp&lsquo; which you will use as a starting point for your program. The program will contain part of the main function as well as all of the function <code>prototypes</code> and <code>headers</code> you will need. Your job will be to</p>\n<ul>\n<li>add in the necessary code within the switch statement win the main function, and</li>\n<li>add in the necessary code using the formulas given above for each of the functions.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Below are the formulas you can use based on the ones shown above</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<blockquote>fact = n* (n-1) * ... * 2 * 1 (Use a loops for this)</blockquote>\n</li>\n<li>\n<blockquote>permutation(n, r) = fact(n) / ( fact(n-r) )</blockquote>\n</li>\n<li>\n<blockquote>combination(n, r) = fact(n) / ( fact(r) * fact(n-r) )</blockquote>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You will have to include these within the appropriate function bodies. Take a look at the sample code below to see an example of how the final product should run.</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, youUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>======================================</code><br /> <code>| Permutation and Combination Menu |</code><br /> <code>======================================</code><br /> <code>| 1) Find the Factorial |</code><br /> <code>| 2) Find the Permutation of n and r |</code><br /> <code>| 3) Find the Combination of n and r |</code><br /> <code>| 4) Exit |</code><br /> <code>======================================</code><br /> <code>Please enter in a option: </code><br /> <code>1</code><br /> <code>Enter the value of n: </code><br /> <code>6</code><br /> <code>The factorial is: 720</code><br /><br />\n<p class="alert alert-warning">&lt;&lt; Menu will be displayed here &gt;&gt;</p>\n<code>Please enter in a option: </code><br /> <code>2</code><br /> <code>Enter the value of n: </code><br /> <code>10</code><br /> <code>Enter the value of r: </code><br /> <code>9</code><br /> <code>The permutation of 10 and 9 is: 3628800</code><br /><br />\n<p class="alert alert-warning">&lt;&lt; Menu will be displayed here &gt;&gt;</p>\n<code>Please enter in a option: </code><br /> <code>2</code><br /> <code>Enter the value of n: </code><br /> <code>5</code><br /> <code>Enter the value of r: </code><br /> <code>6</code><br /> <code>Sorry you cannot have n &lt; r</code><br /><br />\n<p class="alert alert-warning">&lt;&lt; Menu will be displayed here &gt;&gt;</p>\n<code>Please enter in a option: </code><br /> <code>3</code><br /> <code>Enter the value of n: </code><br /> <code>10</code><br /> <code>Enter the value of r: </code><br /> <code>9</code><br /> <code>The combination of 10 and 9 is: 10</code><br /><br />\n<p class="alert alert-warning">&lt;&lt; Menu will be displayed here &gt;&gt;</p>\n<code>Please enter in a option: </code><br /> <code>3</code><br /> <code>Enter the value of n: </code><br /> <code>5</code><br /> <code>Enter the value of r: </code><br /> <code>6</code><br /> <code>Sorry you cannot have n &lt; r</code><br /><br />\n<p class="alert alert-warning">&lt;&lt; Menu will be displayed here &gt;&gt;</p>\n<code>Please enter in a option: </code><br /> <code>4</code><br /> <code> -- Closing Program --</code><br /><br /> <code>(c) 2013, youUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>', 1, 1),
(35, 7, 13, 'structure', 'cpp', 3, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 8, 1, 3, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<p>Your first task is to write a program called structure.cpp. This program should initialize a structure called <strong>Student</strong> and should have member variables:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>string name</code></li>\n<li><code>char letter_grade</code></li>\n<li><code>int credits</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The <code>name</code> variable is the student''s first name and the rest are self explanatory.</p>\n<p>In your main program, create two Student variables, and get the information of all three member variables from the user. Your program should then compare the number of credits of the two variables, and print out the student&rsquo;s information with the higher credits, as well as the student&rsquo;s letter grade.</p>\n<p>Take a look at the sample program below:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program makes use of structures to mange student records.</code><br /><br /> <code>Please enter the records for the first student</code><br /> <code>Student Name: John</code><br /> <code>Credit Hours: 4</code><br /> <code>Letter Grade: A</code><br /><br /> <code>Now enter the records for the second student</code><br /> <code>Student Name: Jane</code><br /> <code>Credit Hours: 3</code><br /> <code>Letter Grade: B</code><br /><br /> <code>John has more credit hours that Jane</code><br /> <code>John''s grade: A</code><br /> <code>Thank you!</code><br /><br /> <code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Suppose the number of credit hours are the same. This is how the program should react:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br /> <code>This program makes use of structures to mange student records.</code><br /><br /> <code>Please enter the records for the first student</code><br /> <code>Student Name: John</code><br /> <code>Credit Hours: 3</code><br /> <code>Letter Grade: B</code><br /><br /> <code>Now enter the records for the second student</code><br /> <code>Student Name: Jack</code><br /> <code>Credit Hours: 3</code><br /> <code>Letter Grade: A</code><br /><br /> <code>Both these students have the same number of credits.</code><br /><br /> <code>Thank you!</code><br /> <code>(c)2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code></blockquote>\n<p>Note that a condition has been placed that displays a different message should the credit hours be equal to each other.</p>', 1, 1),
(36, 7, 13, 'employeeStruc', 'cpp', 2, 1, 1, 0, 2, 1, 2, 16, 1, 4, 1, 1, 7, 1, '<div class="alert"><strong>Warning!</strong>: For this exercise you MUST make use of structures and functions. As there is a lot of data involved if you do not use these you probably will not finish on time!</div>\n<p>Write a program <code>employeeRecords.cpp<code> that makes use of the following record type</code></code></p>\n<blockquote><code>struct Employee</code><br /> <code>{</code><br /> <code> string fname;</code> // Employee First Name<br /> <code> string lname;</code> // Employee Last Name<br /> <code> int id;</code> // Employee ID<br /> <code> int hours;</code> // Hours worked<br /> <code> float rate;</code> // Wage Rate<br /> <code>}</code></blockquote>\n<p>The program should open the file <code>employee.in</code> and read in the 6 records stored within it into the given structures (Look at sample file below). The records are stored in the file with the following format:</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Here is a quick example of how you would store the first and last name from an input stream <em>infile</em> into a structure called emp1.</p>\n<blockquote><code>infile &gt;&gt; emp1.fname &gt;&gt; emp1.lname; </code></blockquote>\n<p>After all the information has been read in you must display a menu listing all the employees last names. When an option is selected that employee''s information should be displayed</p>\n<ul>\n<ul>\n<li>First Name</li>\n<li>Last Name</li>\n<li>Employee ID</li>\n<li>Hours worked</li>\n<li>Wage Rate</li>\n<li>Total wages (hours * rate)</li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<p class="alert">Note: In order to simplify this process it is strongly advised that you use the following functions.</p>\n<blockquote><code>void display(Employee);</code></blockquote>\n<p>As for display function, rather than keep on repeating <code>cout</code> statements in the switch statement of a loop, the employee record could simply be passed to the generic function and every record will be printed exactly the same.</p>\n<p>Here is a sample of how the program should look like along with a sample of the given input file below:</p>\n<blockquote><code>(c) 2013, yourUnixLogin First Last</code><br /><br />\n<p class="alert alert-success">&lt;&lt; This is the Menu&gt;&gt;</p>\n<code>==========================================</code><br /> <code>| Information menu for Employee data |</code><br /> <code>==========================================</code><br /> <code>| 1) Doe</code><br /> <code>| 2) Brown</code><br /> <code>| 3) Tillman</code><br /> <code>| 4) Moss</code><br /> <code>| 5) Frost</code><br /> <code>| 6) Dawson</code><br /> <code>| </code><br /> <code>| 0) Exit</code><br /> <code>==========================================</code><br /><br /> <code><code>Please enter in an option: 1<code><br /><br /></code></code></code>\n<p class="alert alert-success">&lt;&lt; This is the result for the option &gt;&gt;</p>\n<code><code><code><code>===================================</code><br /> <code>Employee info : Doe</code><br /> <code>===================================</code><br /> <code>First Name : John</code><br /> <code>Last Name : Doe</code><br /> <code>Employee ID : 12358</code><br /> <code>Hours : 42</code><br /> <code>Wage Rate : 23.53</code><br /> <code>Wages : 988.26</code><br /> <code>===================================</code><br /><br /></code></code></code>\n<p class="alert alert-success">&lt;&lt; Menu will be displayed here &gt;&gt;</p>\n<code><code><code><code>Please enter in an option: 3</code><br /><br /> <code>===================================</code><br /> <code>Employee info : Tillman</code><br /> <code>===================================</code><br /> <code>First Name : Jane</code><br /> <code>Last Name : Tillman</code><br /> <code>Employee ID : 46873</code><br /> <code>Hours : 43</code><br /> <code>Wage Rate : 28.23</code><br /> <code>Wages : 1213.89</code><br /> <code>===================================</code><br /><br /></code></code></code>\n<p class